To 1996, mainly census figures. From 2001, mainly estimated resident population and relates to 'state suburbs'; see Statistical Geography Volume 1: Australian Standard Geographical Classification (ASGC) 2006, cat. no. 1216.0.

Includes towns, cities, municipalities and boroughs, urban centres and (rural) localities, suburbs and other areas as published, generally with a population of at least 100 persons at some stage. If a town, etc is listed more than once, the data relate to different geographic areas. There may be overlaps in areas shown, especially in larger centres, e.g. suburbs may be shown separately and also included in a city total.
Figures can fluctuate over time due to changes in population, boundary changes, gold, weather, crops, etc.
Census figures are based on location on census night rather than place of usual residence.

An urban centre is an area with a population of 1,000 or more people in one or more adjoining whole collection districts with urban characteristics. A (rural) locality is an area of 200-999 people in one or more adjoining whole collection districts with urban characteristics. They can cross local government area and other boundaries. Thus when population grows to 1,000 or more, a locality becomes an urban centre; when population falls below 1,000 the area is a locality rather than an urban centre. Sometimes an urban centre or a locality becomes part of a larger urban centre or locality as population expands, or was previously part of another urban centre or (rural) locality, and separate figures are not shown. Includes figures for localities where earlier populations were under 200 where available. If a town or locality or more than 200 persons does not appear in this table, it may be included with a nearby town or city. Shows whole collection districts or amalgamations of whole collection districts; this means the population recorded for some areas may seem to increase or decrease sharply between censuses.
For 1861, figures are 'Town portion of police district'.
For 1864, figures are 'Town portion of police districts'.

To 1871, no threshold population size for inclusion in table; for 1876 to 1891, threshold of 40; for 1901, threshold of 100 (this is all that was published); for 1911, threshold of 100, except where an area has a later population of at least 100 or is already in the table from earlier years; from 1933 to 1966, includes towns with a population of 200 or more, and those areas where figures are available that later became an urban centre or locality or where pre-1911 figures were available.

For 1911, figures 'refer to the localities specified, as defined by the residents therein. It must be understood that no clearly defined boundaries exist in these cases, and the population given for any locality represents the number of persons who returned themselves and their dwellings as belonging to that locality'.

For 1981, the Census was held during Queensland schools holidays (end of semester break) for the first time. The number of people away from their usual residence was much higher than in previous census years, leading to larger populations in resort areas and smaller populations in other areas than would usually be the case.
